{
  "In the Leontief input-output model, the equation x = Ax + d is used. What does the vector d represent?": "",
  "The price of each good": "",
  "Total production of each industry": "",
  "External (final) demand from consumers": "",
  "The profit of each industry": "",
  "In the Leontief model x = Ax + d, x is total production, Ax is intermediate demand (what industries consume from each other), and d is the external/final demand from consumers outside the production system.": "",
  "The Leontief input-output model solves for total production x using what formula?": "",
  "x = A^{-1} d": "",
  "x = (I - A)^{-1} d": "",
  "x = d / A": "",
  "x = (A - I) d": "",
  "From x = Ax + d, rearranging gives (I - A)x = d, so x = (I - A)^{-1} d. The matrix (I - A)^{-1} is called the Leontief inverse.": "",
  "A 2-sector economy has consumption matrix A = [[0.2, 0.3],[0.4, 0.1]]. What is I - A?": "",
  "[[-0.8, 0.3],[0.4, -0.9]]": "",
  "[[0.8, 0.3],[0.4, 0.9]]": "",
  "[[0.8, -0.3],[-0.4, 0.9]]": "",
  "[[1.2, -0.3],[-0.4, 1.1]]": "",
  "I - A = [[1,0],[0,1]] - [[0.2,0.3],[0.4,0.1]] = [[1-0.2, 0-0.3],[0-0.4, 1-0.1]] = [[0.8, -0.3],[-0.4, 0.9]].": "",
  "For the consumption matrix A = [[0.2, 0.3],[0.4, 0.1]], what is det(I - A)?": "",
  "0.30": "",
  "0.60": "",
  "0.72": "",
  "0.48": "",
  "I - A = [[0.8, -0.3],[-0.4, 0.9]]. det(I - A) = 0.8*0.9 - (-0.3)*(-0.4) = 0.72 - 0.12 = 0.60. Since the determinant is positive, the system has a unique solution.": "",
  "A country has 3 economic sectors. The consumption matrix A has column sums of 0.5, 0.7, and 0.6. Which sector consumes the highest proportion of total inputs?": "",
  "Sector 2 with column sum 0.7": "",
  "All sectors consume equally": "",
  "Sector 3 with column sum 0.6": "",
  "Sector 1 with column sum 0.5": "",
  "The column sum of the consumption matrix for sector j gives the total input consumed per unit of output for that sector. Sector 2 has the highest column sum (0.7), meaning it requires 70 cents of inputs for each dollar of output.": "",
  "In a Markov model of consumer behavior, if the transition matrix is T = [[0.7, 0.2],[0.3, 0.8]], what fraction of Brand A customers switch to Brand B each period?": "",
  "0.2": "",
  "0.3": "",
  "0.8": "",
  "0.7": "",
  "In the column-stochastic transition matrix, column 1 represents Brand A. T[2][1] = 0.3 means 30% of Brand A customers switch to Brand B each period (and 70% stay with Brand A).": "",
  "A linear programming problem has constraints written as Ax <= b. How many decision variables are there if A is a 5x3 matrix?": "",
  "5": "",
  "3": "",
  "8": "",
  "15": "",
  "In Ax <= b, the matrix A has dimensions m x n where m is the number of constraints and n is the number of decision variables. With A being 5x3, there are 3 decision variables and 5 constraints.": "",
  "In portfolio theory, the variance of a portfolio with weight vector w and covariance matrix C is given by w^T C w. If C = [[4,1],[1,9]] and w = [0.5, 0.5]^T, what is the portfolio variance?": "",
  "2.5": "",
  "6.5": "",
  "3.75": "",
  "Cw = [[4,1],[1,9]]*[0.5,0.5]^T = [2.5, 5]^T. w^T Cw = [0.5,0.5]*[2.5,5]^T = 0.5*2.5 + 0.5*5 = 1.25 + 2.5 = 3.75. The portfolio variance is 3.75.": "",
  "An economy has the consumption matrix A = [[0.1, 0.2],[0.3, 0.2]]. For the economy to be productive (able to meet any demand), all eigenvalues of A must satisfy what condition?": "",
  "The largest eigenvalue must be greater than 1": "",
  "All eigenvalues must have absolute value less than 1": "",
  "All eigenvalues must be positive": "",
  "All eigenvalues must equal 1": "",
  "The Leontief model is productive (meaning (I-A)^{-1} exists and is non-negative) if and only if all eigenvalues of A have absolute value less than 1. This ensures the geometric series I + A + A^2 + ... converges.": "",
  "In game theory, a payoff matrix is P = [[3,-1],[-2,4]]. In a zero-sum game, if Player 1 chooses row 1 and Player 2 chooses column 2, what is Player 1's payoff?": "",
  "-1": "",
  "-2": "",
  "4": "",
  "The payoff matrix entry P[1][2] gives Player 1's payoff when Player 1 chooses row 1 and Player 2 chooses column 2. P[1][2] = -1, meaning Player 1 loses 1 unit.": "",
  "What is the 'Leontief input-output model' in economics?": "",
  "A model for predicting stock market prices using matrix multiplication": "",
  "A mathematical model that uses a system of linear equations to describe the interdependencies between sectors of an economy": "",
  "A statistical model for forecasting unemployment rates": "",
  "A method for computing GDP using eigenvalue decomposition": "",
  "The Leontief input-output model represents an economy as interconnected sectors where each sector's output is consumed by other sectors. The linear system x = Ax + d captures how production must satisfy both inter-industry demand (Ax) and final demand (d).": "",
  "What does 'consumption matrix' (or technology matrix) mean in the Leontief model?": "",
  "A matrix recording total consumer spending by sector": "",
  "A matrix showing the final demand for each sector's goods": "",
  "A matrix A where entry a_{ij} represents the amount of sector i's output needed to produce one unit of sector j's output": "",
  "A matrix of tax rates applied to each sector": "",
  "The consumption matrix A has entries a_{ij} giving the amount of good i consumed per unit of output of good j. Column j of A lists the input requirements for producing one unit of sector j's output.": "",
  "What is the 'Leontief inverse' in the input-output model?": "",
  "The inverse of the consumption matrix A^{-1}": "",
  "The matrix (I - A)^{-1} that transforms final demand into required total production": "",
  "The negative of the identity minus A": "",
  "The transpose of the technology matrix": "",
  "The Leontief inverse (I - A)^{-1} can be expanded as I + A + A^2 + A^3 + ... (when convergent), capturing both direct and indirect input requirements. It maps external demand d to total production x = (I-A)^{-1}d.": "",
  "What does 'productive economy' mean in the context of the Leontief model?": "",
  "An economy where all sectors produce the same amount": "",
  "An economy where (I - A)^{-1} exists and has all non-negative entries, meaning any non-negative demand can be met": "",
  "An economy with positive GDP growth under the given assumptions": "",
  "An economy with no imports, particularly regarding leontief based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "An economy is productive if the Leontief inverse (I-A)^{-1} exists and is non-negative. This means for any non-negative demand vector d, there exists a non-negative production vector x that satisfies it.": "",
  "What is a 'covariance matrix' in financial economics?": "",
  "A symmetric positive semi-definite matrix where entry (i,j) measures the covariance between asset i and asset j returns": "",
  "A matrix of expected returns for different portfolios": "",
  "A diagonal matrix of asset variances": "",
  "A matrix of correlation coefficients between stocks": "",
  "The covariance matrix C has diagonal entries C_{ii} = Var(r_i) (the variance of asset i's return) and off-diagonal entries C_{ij} = Cov(r_i, r_j). It is always symmetric and positive semi-definite.": "",
  "What does 'linear programming' refer to in economics?": "",
  "Writing computer programs that process economic data in a linear fashion": "",
  "A method for linearizing nonlinear economic models": "",
  "An optimization technique that maximizes or minimizes a linear objective function subject to linear constraints, often represented using matrix inequalities": "",
  "Programming economic simulations using linear algebra libraries": "",
  "Linear programming finds the optimal value of a linear function c^T x subject to constraints Ax <= b and x >= 0. It is widely used in economics for resource allocation, production planning, and transportation problems.": "",
  "What is a 'transition matrix' in economic Markov models?": "",
  "The inverse of the input-output matrix": "",
  "A matrix of import and export values between countries": "",
  "A stochastic matrix where entry T_{ij} gives the probability of transitioning from state j to state i": "",
  "A matrix describing how prices transition from one period to the next": "",
  "In economic Markov models (e.g., brand switching, employment status), the transition matrix T has entry T_{ij} giving the probability of moving from state j to state i. Each column sums to 1.": "",
  "What does 'equilibrium price vector' mean in exchange models?": "",
  "A vector of maximum possible prices": "",
  "The price vector that maximizes producer profit": "",
  "The eigenvector of the demand matrix": "",
  "A price vector p such that total supply equals total demand in all markets simultaneously": "",
  "An equilibrium price vector balances all markets simultaneously, meaning the excess demand is zero for all goods. In linear models, this often reduces to solving a system of linear equations for the price vector.": "",
  "What is 'Markowitz portfolio optimization'?": "",
  "A method that uses the covariance matrix to find the portfolio weights that minimize risk for a given expected return": "",
  "A technique for maximizing the trace of the return matrix": "",
  "A method for diversifying investments based on the determinant of the price matrix": "",
  "An algorithm for finding the eigenvalues of stock price data": "",
  "Markowitz portfolio optimization minimizes portfolio variance w^T C w subject to constraints on expected return w^T mu = target and budget w^T 1 = 1. The solution uses the covariance matrix C and expected return vector mu.": "",
  "What does 'saddle point' mean in the context of game theory payoff matrices?": "",
  "An entry that is simultaneously the minimum of its row and the maximum of its column, representing a pure strategy Nash equilibrium": "",
  "A zero entry in the payoff matrix, particularly regarding pure following conventional understanding": "",
  "The determinant of the payoff matrix, particularly regarding mean when evaluated systematically": "",
  "The entry with the largest absolute value in the matrix when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "A saddle point in a payoff matrix is an entry that is the smallest in its row (best response for the row player's minimization) and the largest in its column (best response for the column player's maximization). It represents a stable pure strategy equilibrium.": "",
  "An economist models a 2-sector economy with consumption matrix A = [[0.1, 0.4],[0.3, 0.2]] and final demand d = [100, 200]^T. They compute I - A = [[0.9, -0.4],[-0.3, 0.8]]. What is det(I - A)?": "",
  "0.36": "",
  "det(I - A) = 0.9*0.8 - (-0.4)*(-0.3) = 0.72 - 0.12 = 0.60. Since this is positive, the Leontief inverse exists and the economy can satisfy the demand.": "",
  "Continuing from the previous economy with (I-A) = [[0.9,-0.4],[-0.3,0.8]] and d = [100,200]^T, the economist computes (I-A)^{-1} = (1/0.6)*[[0.8,0.4],[0.3,0.9]]. What is the total production vector x?": "",
  "[200, 300]^T": "",
  "[100, 200]^T": "",
  "[266.67, 350]^T (approximately)": "",
  "[333.33, 166.67]^T": "",
  "x = (I-A)^{-1}d = (1/0.6)*[[0.8,0.4],[0.3,0.9]]*[100,200]^T = (1/0.6)*[0.8*100+0.4*200, 0.3*100+0.9*200]^T = (1/0.6)*[160, 210]^T = [266.67, 350]^T.": "",
  "A financial analyst has 3 assets with covariance matrix C = [[4,2,0],[2,9,3],[0,3,16]]. They want to invest equally in all three (w = [1/3,1/3,1/3]^T). What is the portfolio variance w^T C w?": "",
  "4.33 (approximately)": "",
  "3.22, particular": "",
  "9.67, particular": "",
  "29, particularly": "",
  "Cw = [[4,2,0],[2,9,3],[0,3,16]]*[1/3,1/3,1/3]^T = [6/3, 14/3, 19/3]^T = [2, 14/3, 19/3]^T. w^T Cw = (1/3)*2 + (1/3)*(14/3) + (1/3)*(19/3) = 2/3 + 14/9 + 19/9 = 6/9 + 14/9 + 19/9 = 39/9 = 4.33.": "",
  "An economist uses a Markov chain to model employment. The transition matrix is T = [[0.9, 0.3],[0.1, 0.7]] (columns: employed, unemployed). Starting with 80% employed and 20% unemployed, what is the employment rate after one period?": "",
  "78%": "",
  "90%": "",
  "85%": "",
  "72%": "",
  "x_1 = T*x_0 = [[0.9,0.3],[0.1,0.7]]*[0.8,0.2]^T = [0.9*0.8+0.3*0.2, 0.1*0.8+0.7*0.2]^T = [0.72+0.06, 0.08+0.14]^T = [0.78, 0.22]^T. Employment rate is 78%.": "",
  "A trade economist models 3 countries exchanging goods. The exchange matrix is E = [[0.6,0.2,0.1],[0.3,0.5,0.3],[0.1,0.3,0.6]]. What percentage of Country 1's production stays within Country 1?": "",
  "10%": "",
  "60%": "",
  "30%": "",
  "40%": "",
  "In the exchange matrix, column 1 represents the distribution of Country 1's production. E[1][1] = 0.6 means 60% of Country 1's production stays in Country 1. The remaining 40% is exported (30% to Country 2, 10% to Country 3).": "",
  "A game theorist analyzes a 2-player zero-sum game with payoff matrix P = [[4, -2],[-1, 3]]. Player 1 uses mixed strategy [p, 1-p] and Player 2 uses mixed strategy [q, 1-q]. What is Player 1's expected payoff as a function of p and q?": "",
  "4pq - 2p(1-q) - (1-p)q + 3(1-p)(1-q)": "",
  "4pq + 3(1-p)(1-q)": "",
  "4p + 3q": "",
  "(4-2)p + (-1+3)q": "",
  "The expected payoff is the weighted sum of all entries: E = p*q*P[1][1] + p*(1-q)*P[1][2] + (1-p)*q*P[2][1] + (1-p)*(1-q)*P[2][2] = 4pq - 2p(1-q) - (1-p)q + 3(1-p)(1-q).": "",
  "A supply chain manager uses the Leontief model for a 3-sector economy. If final demand for sector 2 increases by 10 units while sectors 1 and 3 stay the same, the change in total production is delta_x = (I-A)^{-1} * [0,10,0]^T. This equals the second column of (I-A)^{-1} multiplied by 10. Why?": "",
  "Because the Leontief inverse is always diagonal": "",
  "Because sectors are independent in the input-output model": "",
  "Because multiplying a matrix by a vector with only one non-zero entry selects and scales the corresponding column": "",
  "Because the change in demand only affects sector 2": "",
  "When you multiply a matrix M by a vector with only the j-th entry non-zero (value c), the result is c times the j-th column of M. So (I-A)^{-1}*[0,10,0]^T = 10 * (column 2 of (I-A)^{-1}), showing the ripple effect through all sectors.": "",
  "An agricultural economist models a 2-sector economy (farming and manufacturing). The consumption matrix is A = [[0.3, 0.1],[0.2, 0.4]]. To check if the economy is productive, they verify that all column sums are less than 1. Are the column sums less than 1?": "",
  "No: column 2 sums to 1.0": "",
  "Yes: column sums are 0.4 and 0.5": "",
  "Yes: column sums are 0.5 and 0.5, both less than 1": "",
  "No: column 1 sums to 1.5": "",
  "Column 1 sum: 0.3 + 0.2 = 0.5. Column 2 sum: 0.1 + 0.4 = 0.5. Both are less than 1, confirming the economy is productive (each sector consumes less than it produces). This is a sufficient condition for (I-A)^{-1} to exist and be non-negative.": "",
  "A pension fund manager has a portfolio of 2 assets with expected returns mu = [8%, 12%]^T and covariance matrix C = [[4, -1],[-1, 9]]. What is the expected return of the portfolio with weights w = [0.6, 0.4]^T?": "",
  "9.6%": "",
  "11.2%": "",
  "8.8%": "",
  "Expected return = w^T * mu = 0.6*8% + 0.4*12% = 4.8% + 4.8% = 9.6%. The portfolio expected return is a weighted average of individual asset returns.": "",
  "An economist studies the long-run behavior of a brand-switching Markov chain with T = [[0.7, 0.4],[0.3, 0.6]]. The steady-state vector q satisfies Tq = q and q1 + q2 = 1. What is the steady-state distribution?": "",
  "q = [4/7, 3/7]^T": "",
  "q = [1/2, 1/2]^T": "",
  "q = [3/7, 4/7]^T": "",
  "q = [0.7, 0.3]^T": "",
  "From Tq = q: 0.7*q1 + 0.4*q2 = q1 gives -0.3*q1 + 0.4*q2 = 0, so q2 = (3/4)*q1. With q1 + q2 = 1: q1 + (3/4)*q1 = 1, so (7/4)*q1 = 1, giving q1 = 4/7 and q2 = 3/7.": ""
